\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Scaling relations analysis of 24 Herschel filaments. Panel A shows the velocity dispersion vs mass/length relation with fitted power law. Panel B shows the width distribution. The measured log-log exponent $\alpha = 0.49 \pm 0.03$ is consistent with the virial prediction of $0.5$ at $0.33\sigma $, while the virial amplitude shows a 2.7$\sigma $ deficit ($A_{\mathrm  {meas}} = 0.0812$ vs $A_{\mathrm  {theory}} \approx 0.0928$\,km\,s$^{-1}$\,(M$_\odot $\,pc$^{-1}$)$^{-0.5}$). The universal width ($0.098 \pm 0.019$\nobreakspace  {}pc) is consistent with the characteristic dissipation scale in molecular clouds.}}{6}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:scaling}{{2}{6}{Scaling relations analysis of 24 Herschel filaments. Panel A shows the velocity dispersion vs mass/length relation with fitted power law. Panel B shows the width distribution. The measured log-log exponent $\alpha = 0.49 \pm 0.03$ is consistent with the virial prediction of $0.5$ at $0.33\sigma $, while the virial amplitude shows a 2.7$\sigma $ deficit ($A_{\mathrm {meas}} = 0.0812$ vs $A_{\mathrm {theory}} \approx 0.0928$\,km\,s$^{-1}$\,(M$_\odot $\,pc$^{-1}$)$^{-0.5}$). The universal width ($0.098 \pm 0.019$~pc) is consistent with the characteristic dissipation scale in molecular clouds}{figure.2}{}}
