\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Bayesian model selection for 24 Herschel filaments. Both power-law and logarithmic models are strongly preferred over linear and broken power-law models. The power-law model is theoretically motivated by the virial theorem. The measured virial exponent ($\alpha = 0.49 \pm 0.03$) is consistent with the virial prediction of $0.5$ at $0.33\sigma $, while the virial amplitude shows a 2.7$\sigma $ deficit ($A_{\mathrm  {meas}}/A_{\mathrm  {theory}} = 0.88$), likely attributable to distance systematics or non-virial support.}}{11}{figure.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:bayesian}{{6}{11}{Bayesian model selection for 24 Herschel filaments. Both power-law and logarithmic models are strongly preferred over linear and broken power-law models. The power-law model is theoretically motivated by the virial theorem. The measured virial exponent ($\alpha = 0.49 \pm 0.03$) is consistent with the virial prediction of $0.5$ at $0.33\sigma $, while the virial amplitude shows a 2.7$\sigma $ deficit ($A_{\mathrm {meas}}/A_{\mathrm {theory}} = 0.88$), likely attributable to distance systematics or non-virial support}{figure.6}{}}
\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Model comparison results. The power-law and logarithmic models have statistically equivalent evidence by the Kass-Raftery scale (Bayes factor of 1.2 is ``not worth more than a bare mention''). Both are preferred over the linear model. Log evidence values are from harmonic mean estimation (HME); note that HME is known to overestimate absolute log-evidences, so Bayes factors between models (ratios of evidences) are more reliable than the absolute log-evidence values \citep  {kass1995}. Readers should treat the large Bayes factors as upper bounds on the true preference --- the actual Bayes factors are likely smaller due to HME over-estimation of log-evidences.}}{11}{table.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:model_comparison}{{2}{11}{Model comparison results. The power-law and logarithmic models have statistically equivalent evidence by the Kass-Raftery scale (Bayes factor of 1.2 is ``not worth more than a bare mention''). Both are preferred over the linear model. Log evidence values are from harmonic mean estimation (HME); note that HME is known to overestimate absolute log-evidences, so Bayes factors between models (ratios of evidences) are more reliable than the absolute log-evidence values \citep {kass1995}. Readers should treat the large Bayes factors as upper bounds on the true preference --- the actual Bayes factors are likely smaller due to HME over-estimation of log-evidences}{table.2}{}}
